benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: PUT /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/customFields - Modify custom fields to bundle

covered: Valid Request: Numerous scenarios (TC01, TC02, TC17, TC23, TC25) cover successful updates with valid payloads and headers.
Non-Existing Resource: TC05 covers 404 for missing bundle.
Partial Update: TC24 tests partial updates to existing fields.
Concurrency/Load: TC18 covers peak load with concurrent requests; TC17 covers normal load performance.

Error Handling: TC04 (invalid bundleId 400), TC07 (malformed body 400), TC08 (missing body 400), TC09 (unsupported fields 400), TC12 (security input 400), TC11 (service unavailable 503), TC20 (integration data 500), TC21 (transient failure retry 204 on retry).
State Variations: TC22 (bundle with no existing fields), TC23 (update existing fields), TC25 (backward compatibility).
Edge Cases: TC13 (max fields), TC14 (max value length), TC15 (empty value), TC16 (unexpected URL parameter).
Regression/Integration: TC19 (special characters), TC20 (inconsistent data from dependent service).
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination handling (not typically applicable to PUT, but frameworks/tests often verify listing/pagination for related GET endpoints).
Caching/ETag: No scenarios validating caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) for PUT responses.
Rate Limiting: No tests addressing rate limiting/throttling behavior for bulk/rapid PUT requests.
Explicit Concurrency Edge Case: While TC18 covers load with concurrency, explicit race-condition scenarios (two clients updating the same bundle at overlapping times) are not standalone.
Authorization Edge: Only 401 tested; no explicit 403/insufficient-permissions scenario.
recommendations: Add a dedicated test for race-condition/concurrent-update scenarios to ensure proper locking/consistency when multiple clients update the same bundle simultaneously.
Include tests for caching headers behavior after PUT (eTag validation, Cache-Control) to confirm proper cache semantics.
Add rate-limiting/throttling tests to validate behavior under bursty PUT requests.
Consider an explicit 403 scenario for authenticated users lacking required permissions to modify bundle custom fields.
